    "summary": "Pepi II Neferkare was a pharaoh of the Sixth Dynasty of Egypt who reigned from approximately 2278 to 2184 BC. Ancient Egyptian sources credited him with a reign of up to 94 years, which, if accurate, would make it the longest reign of any monarch in recorded history. Modern Egyptologists debate the precise length, but even conservative estimates place his rule among the longest documented in antiquity. He came to power as a young child, and his elderly rule coincided with the decline of the [[event:41|Old Kingdom of Egypt]].\n\nThe latter decades of Pepi II's extraordinarily long reign were marked by weakening central authority, the growing power of provincial governors known as nomarchs, and increasing difficulties in organizing the large-scale state projects that had characterized earlier dynasties. Famine, drought, and administrative fragmentation contributed to the collapse that followed his death, leading Egypt into the [[event:1717|First Intermediate Period]] — an era of political disunity lasting roughly a century. Pepi II thus occupies a paradoxical place in history, remembered simultaneously for the remarkable duration of his reign and for his association with one of Egypt's most dramatic political collapses.",
